        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "For use in our company product I've developed some additional features for Zend_Db_Table_Row_Abstract (or an extending class). Currently they live in an extended class in our code, but I think they might be useful for other people too.\r\n\r\nHere's a short overview of the functions:\r\n{{_getReference($ruleKey)}}:\r\nGet reference (part from reference map) for $ruleKey.\r\n\r\n{{_tableToReference(Zend_Db_Table_Abstract $table)}}:\r\nReturn the string reference to the table so it can be used in functions requiring the string reference.\r\n\r\n{{isValidReference()}}:\r\nCheck if this row can be used as a valid reference (I.e. saved and PK not modified).\r\n\r\n{{setReference(Zend_Db_Table_Row_Abstract $row, $ruleKey = null)}}:\r\nModify columns in this so they reference $row according to $ruleKey.\r\n\r\n{{unsetReference($table, $ruleKey = null)}}:\r\nInverse behaviour of setReference.\r\n\r\n{{createDependentRow($table, $ruleKey = null)}}:\r\nCreate a new row from the dependent table, set references to $this and return the row.\r\n\r\n{{createDependentRowByRule($ruleKey)}}:\r\nSame as above, except that it only needs a ruleKey.\r\n\r\n{{findParentRowByRule($rule)}}:\r\nFind parent row by rule instead of by table (rule is always unique).\r\n\r\nSome of these functions could easily be used from within __call, making references between tables even easier than they were. Also, the functions that only use $ruleKey instead of a table class or definition identifier will make it easier for people to rename table classes as long as the rule keys stay the same, or move between table classes and table definitions.\r\n\r\nI will attach my abstract class implementing these functions."
        },
